      <text xml:space="preserve">{{Tanakh OT}}The '''Book of Micah''' is the sixth book of the [[Twelve Minor Prophets|twelve minor prophets]] in the [[Hebrew Bible|Hebrew]] and [[Bible|Christian Bible]].

==Authorship==
{{Books of the Old Testament}}
[[Micah (prophet)|Micah of Moresheth]] (most likely the same city as Moresheth-Gath, mentioned in Micah) prophesied during the days of King [[Hezekiah]] of [[Kingdom of Judah|Judah]]. This paraphrase of [[Book of Jeremiah|Jeremiah]] 26:18 contains practically everything we know of the Prophet himself. Moresheth-Gath was most likely a small town in southwestern Judah {{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}.
	Some scholars{{Who|date=September 2010}} argue over how much of the '''book of Micah''' can be attributed to Micah himself. There is general consensus{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}} that the majority of chapters 1&amp;ndash;3 are in fact Micah’s own (excluding 2:12&amp;ndash;13). The remaining passages are seen by some{{Who|date=September 2010}} as redactions.

However some Old Testament scholars, for example Dr [[Bruce Waltke]] in [[Inter-Varsity Press|IVP]]`s 'New Bible Commentary', defend Micah's authorship of the entire book.

==Date of composition==
Micah was active in Judah from before the fall of Samaria (1:2&amp;ndash;7) in 722 BC; he lived under king Ahaz (735&amp;ndash;715 BC) and king Hezekiah (715&amp;ndash;687), and (apparently) experienced the devastation brought on by Senacherib’s invasion of Judah (701 BC). The heading of the book (1:1) also adds the name of king Jotham (742&amp;ndash;735 BC). This would make Micah active from 742 (at earliest) to 701 (at latest) BC.
The message in [[wikisource:Bible (King James)/Micah#1:2|Micah 1:2–9]] was given before the destruction of Samaria in 721. The appeal of [[Jeremiah]]'s supporters to the [[prophecy]] of Micah confirms his connection with Hezekiah: &quot;And some of the land arose and said to all the assembled people, Micah of Moresheth prophesied during the days of Hezekiah king of Judah&quot; ([[wikisource:Bible (King James)/Jeremiah#26:17|Jeremiah 26:17]]).

==Setting==
During the reigns of Uzziah, king of Judah, and Jeroboam II, king of Israel, a period of relative peace and prosperity began to wane. This was in part due to the rise of the nation of [[Assyria]], who, after a period of quiescence, became a potent political force in the Near East. With the rise of Assyria came a rise in military pressure upon the kingdoms of Judah and Israel.

At the same time that trade and commerce was flourishing, rich landowners were bribing Judges to look favorably upon illicit land acquisitions resulting in a rapid disappearance of small farmers. Those who were dispossessed drifted from the countryside to the cities, which led to overcrowding in the major population centers. Micah outspokenly refuted practices that infringed upon the rights of small farmers resulting in economic gains for rich landowners.

Micah, and the other minor prophets, also speak out against the lack of obedience to the Covenantal stipulations. Many aspects of the covenant had been abandoned in favor of Baal-worship and other Pagan practices. In this light, Samaria, one of the leaders in this apostasy, is condemned to destruction.

Micah’s period of activity also overlaps that of Isaiah’s, and it is possible that the two contemporaries were often mistaken for one another. Jeremaiah 26:18&amp;ndash;20 speaks of Micah’s effect on the king, and that he and the king not only were able to meet, but also that Micah’s message was able to bring the king to repentance. However, some scholars view that it may be more probable that Isaiah was the one who caused the king’s repentance, as he, having access to the king, was much more likely to influence the king’s decisions.

==Content==

While the book of Micah is relatively short, it contains a number of genres and presents a wide variety of content. This includes &quot;lament (1.8-16; 7.8-10), theophany (1.3-4), and hymnic prayer of petition and confidence (7.14-20). &quot; &lt;ref&gt;Coogan, Michael David. ''A Brief INtroduction to the Old testament: The Hebrew Bible in Its Context.'' New Your: Oxford University Press, 2009. Page 284&lt;/ref&gt; 

Micah also includes an example of &quot;covenant lawsuit&quot; (6.1-8). &quot;''Covenant Lawsuit''&quot; is a distinct genre, &quot;in which, Yahweh sues Israel for breach of contract, that is, for violation of the Sinai covenant&quot; &lt;ref&gt;Coogan, Michael David. ''A Brief INtroduction to the Old testament: The Hebrew Bible in Its Context.'' New Your: Oxford University Press, 2009. Page 265&lt;/ref&gt; This section concludes with &quot;what does the Lord require of you? But to do justice, love kindness and walk humbly with your God&quot;; this scripture is an example seen throughout prophetic literature attacking empty rituals and for sincere sacrifice of self to God. Micah shares this content feature with the prophetic books of [[Isaiah]], [[Jeremiah]] and [[Hosea]].&lt;ref&gt;Coogan, Michael David. ''A Brief INtroduction to the Old testament: The Hebrew Bible in Its Context.'' New Your: Oxford University Press, 2009. Page 262&lt;/ref&gt;

'''Poetic Ideas of Micah, according the Anchor Bible Dictionary:'''

* '''The Heading (1:1)''': As is typical of prophetic books, an anonymous editor has supplied the name of the prophet, an indication of his time of activity, and an identification of his speech as the “word of Yahweh.” Samaria and Jerusalem are given prominence as the foci of the prophet’s attention.
* '''Punishment of Samaria (1:2&amp;ndash;7):''' Drawing upon ancient traditions for depicting a theophany, the prophet depicts the coming of Yahweh to punish the idolatrous city.
* '''A transitional Lament (1:8&amp;ndash;9):''' depicting the prophet’s own grief at the calamity leading to the new subject: the doom of Judah and Jerusalem.
* '''A Taunt or Lament over Judah (1:10&amp;ndash;16):''' describes the destruction of the lesser towns of Judah, either as already suffered or as to come (this latter point evidently referring to the invasion of Judah by Sennacherib, 701 BC). N.B. For these passages of doom that will befall the various cities, the device paronomasia is used. Paronomasia is a literary device which 'plays' on the sound of each word for literary effect. For example, the inhabitants of Beth-le-aphrah (“house of dust”) are told to “roll yourselves in the dust.” 1:14. Though most of the Paronomasia is lost in translation, it is the equivalent of ‘Ashdod shall be but ashes,’ where the fate of the city matches its name.
* '''Two Successive Doom speeches (2:1&amp;ndash;5, 6&amp;ndash;11)''': introduce themes characteristic of the prophet Micah as champion of the oppressed small landholder. These speeches warn of the impending doom that will befall those who accumulate land from the sacred community.
* '''The Divine Shepherd King (2:12&amp;ndash;13):''' is pictured as gathering and leading a dispersed people. Though all agree that this passage is not connected to its immediate textual context, there is still debate over whether this is actually Micah’s own words.
* '''Speech against the courts (3:1&amp;ndash;4):''' which focuses on the judges who are allowing illicit land acquisition.
* '''Speech against the prophets (3:5&amp;ndash;8):''' that depicts the prophets who were members of the prophetic guilds at that time as venal and blind.
* '''Climactic Speech about Zion (3:9&amp;ndash;12)''' resumes the indictment of judges and prophets, adds a line against priests and culminates in the famous saying, “Zion shall be plowed as a field.”
* '''The Coming Kingdom of God (4:1&amp;ndash;5)''' centered at the sacred mountain, Zion, this passage shares themes with Isaiah (2:2&amp;ndash;4), preaching universal justice, peace, and security. The remainder of the chapter is made up of poems that focus on the glorious future:
* '''The Kingdom of the Gathered Exiles (4:6&amp;ndash;7)'''
* '''Zion’s Rule Restored (4:8)'''
* '''Deliverance from Distress in Babylon (4:9&amp;ndash;10)'''
* '''The Threshing of Enemies (4:11&amp;ndash;13)'''
* '''The Humiliation of the King (4:14):''' Some scholars consider this a fragment that is incomplete, though it still serves its purpose to introduce the theme of the royal Messiah.
* '''The Return of the Great Ruler from Bethlehem (5:1&amp;ndash;4):''' this foretold king is very influential among the book’s Christian interpreters. Among Christians, it is interpreted to foretell the coming of Christ (&quot;ruler in Israel&quot;) who is eternal (&quot;whose origins are from the old, from the ancient of times&quot;).&lt;ref&gt;The New International Version (NIV) [http://www.biblegateway.com/ Bible]&lt;/ref&gt;The remainder of this chapter’s poems are focused on expounding on the coming peace
* '''Assyria Eliminated (5:4&amp;ndash;5)'''
* '''The Irresistible Might of Jacob (5:6&amp;ndash;8)'''
* '''The Purified Nation (5:9&amp;ndash;14):''' Alien elements that offend Yahweh are removed
* '''A Covenant lawsuit (6:1&amp;ndash;5):''' that represents God as indicting his people for breach of their covenant.
* '''Torah Liturgy (6:6&amp;ndash;8):''' which begins with [[Micah (Prophet)|Micah]] speaking on behalf of the community asking what they should do in order to get back on God's good side. Micah then responds in V. 8 by showing what is God requires: &quot;to Do Justice, and to Love Kindness, and to Walk Humbly with your God.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;NRSV Micah 6:8b&lt;/ref&gt; Thus declaring that the burnt offering of both animals and humans (which may have been practiced in Judah under Kings [[Ahaziah of Judah|Ahaz]] and [[Manasseh of Judah|Manasseh]]) is not necessary for God.&lt;ref&gt;King, Phillip J., ''Harper Collins Study Bible: Micah''; '''NRSV'''; pg. 1246-1247; Revised by Carol J. Dempsey&lt;/ref&gt;
* '''The City as a Cheat (6:9&amp;ndash;16):''' It is unsure whether it is Jerusalem or Samaria, but the city is reprimanded for its dishonest trade practices.
* '''A Disintegrated Society (7:1&amp;ndash;7):''' gives a grim picture of the loss of trust due to the dishonesty of the society.
* '''A Prophetic Liturgy (7:8&amp;ndash;20):''' has been known by this designation since the studies of H. Gunkel (in 1924). It is a ‘liturgy’ due to the alteration of speakers, the combination of themes, and the progression of mood.

==Oracles Outline==
The book of Micah consists of oracles of judgment against [[Kingdom of Judah|Judah]] as well as oracles of restoration as shown in the following outline.
:1.1       Superscription
:1.2-2.11  Oracles of judgment
:2.12-13   Oracles of restoration
:3.1-12    Oracles of judgment
:4.1-5.15  Oracles of restoration
:6.1-7.6   Oracles of judgment
:7.7-20    Oracles of restoration &lt;ref&gt;Coogan, Michael. ''A Brief Introduction to the Old Testament''. Oxford University Press, 2009.&lt;/ref&gt;

